00:33:38,440 --> 00:33:39,810
Two, three.

757
00:33:40,270 --> 00:33:42,010
- Thank you.
- Thank you!

758
00:33:42,070 --> 00:33:43,940
- Help yourselves.
- Thank you.

759
00:33:45,010 --> 00:33:50,050
STRAIGHT INTO HIS MOUTH

760
00:33:51,050 --> 00:33:52,480
EXCLAIMING

761
00:33:55,620 --> 00:33:59,730
A WILD, PRIMAL RIB-EATING SHOW

762
00:34:01,090 --> 00:34:02,190
I feel like a bandit.

763
00:34:02,960 --> 00:34:04,230
Eat up.

764
00:34:06,060 --> 00:34:09,400
HE OPENS WIDE AND TAKES A HUGE BITE

765
00:34:09,470 --> 00:34:11,740
SLURPING

766
00:34:12,440 --> 00:34:14,540
SATISFIED

767
00:34:15,910 --> 00:34:18,680
OVER HERE, HE'S DEVOURING THE RIBS

768
00:34:18,740 --> 00:34:19,750
EXCLAIMING

769
00:34:21,010 --> 00:34:23,650
HE EXCLAIMS AT EVERY SINGLE BITE

770
00:34:23,720 --> 00:34:24,780
EXCLAIMING

771
00:34:25,450 --> 00:34:26,490
This is insane.

772
00:34:26,950 --> 00:34:28,650
YOU'RE EATING WELL

773
00:34:28,920 --> 00:34:30,890
- You should have a bite.
- What? No.

774
00:34:31,460 --> 00:34:32,820
You guys eat.

775
00:34:32,890 --> 00:34:34,230
YOU GUYS EAT UP

776
00:34:35,560 --> 00:34:39,400
THANK YOU, RAIN

777
00:34:40,970 --> 00:34:44,370
BIG BITE

778
00:34:46,540 --> 00:34:49,780
THE FLAVOR OF THESE RIBS IS
IMPOSSIBLE TO STOP

779
00:34:53,850 --> 00:34:58,180
HE TILTS HIS HEAD TO GNAW AWAY

780
00:34:59,320 --> 00:35:00,620
Do you want more salt?

781
00:35:01,320 --> 00:35:02,820
- Salt. No?
- No.

782
00:35:02,890 --> 00:35:04,320
IT'S PERFECT AS IT IS

783
00:35:04,390 --> 00:35:05,890
I've never eaten a rib like this.

784
00:35:06,790 --> 00:35:10,060
This is my first time
holding the bone while eating it.

785
00:35:11,360 --> 00:35:12,660
- RAIN.
- Yes?

786
00:35:12,730 --> 00:35:14,130
I don't need your autograph
on my T-shirt.

787
00:35:14,200 --> 00:35:15,200
Got it.

788
00:35:16,640 --> 00:35:17,770
This beef is enough for me.

789
00:35:20,070 --> 00:35:24,280
HE'S ALREADY COMPLETELY IN LOVE
WITH THE RIBS

790
00:35:24,340 --> 00:35:26,680
PLEASED

791
00:35:27,310 --> 00:35:32,220
THEIR RIB-EATING SHOW CONTINUES

792
00:35:33,550 --> 00:35:34,890
I MUST TAKE PHOTOS

793
00:35:34,950 --> 00:35:36,090
CHEWING

794
00:35:36,150 --> 00:35:38,520
BO GUM, you look
too boyish right now.

795
00:35:38,590 --> 00:35:39,790
Give me a bandit look.

796
00:35:39,860 --> 00:35:41,530
ASKING HIM TO ACT LIKE A BANDIT

797
00:35:42,860 --> 00:35:44,560
HE PUTS ON A FIERCE LOOK

798
00:35:45,230 --> 00:35:47,370
A BOYISH BANDIT

799
00:35:47,770 --> 00:35:49,600
SATISFIED

800
00:35:49,670 --> 00:35:50,840
LAUGHING

801
00:35:50,900 --> 00:35:52,400
Just like that!

802
00:35:52,940 --> 00:35:55,140
THERE'S THE PERFECT BANDIT

803
00:35:55,710 --> 00:35:57,840
A BANDIT WITH A BIG APPETITE

804
00:35:58,640 --> 00:35:59,650
THE MEAT PARTY ISN'T OVER YET

805
00:35:59,710 --> 00:36:00,710
This is insane.

806
00:36:01,510 --> 00:36:04,450
PUTTING SKIRT STEAK INTO BEEF FAT

807
00:36:05,520 --> 00:36:08,220
SIZZLING

808
00:36:09,120 --> 00:36:12,560
THE JUICES ARE SEALED IN BY THE OIL

809
00:36:12,620 --> 00:36:14,790
Just a second. Yes, let's flip it.

810
00:36:15,460 --> 00:36:17,960
EVERYONE IS AMAZED

811
00:36:21,600 --> 00:36:28,970
CRISPY ON THE OUTSIDE

812
00:36:30,080 --> 00:36:34,210
AFTER SEARING IT IN OIL FIRST

813
00:36:35,580 --> 00:36:40,550
HE PUTS IT ON THE GRILL
TO ADD THAT SMOKY FLAVOR

814
00:36:41,390 --> 00:36:42,890
TRY THIS MEAT AS WELL

815
00:36:42,950 --> 00:36:44,560
This is a different cut.

816
00:36:45,490 --> 00:36:47,260
- I'll cut it up for you.
- Which cut is it?

817
00:36:47,730 --> 00:36:49,530
It's skirt steak.

818
00:36:49,590 --> 00:36:52,360
BEAUTIFULLY BROWNED SKIRT STEAK

819
00:36:52,700 --> 00:36:54,270
It's cooked perfectly
along the grain, right?

820
00:36:55,070 --> 00:36:58,640
CRISPY OUTSIDE BUT JUICY INSIDE

821
00:37:00,010 --> 00:37:01,310
That's crazy.

822
00:37:01,640 --> 00:37:02,940
- What do I do?
- And then...

823
00:37:03,010 --> 00:37:05,240
- I could just eat it as is.
- Put one on top.

824
00:37:05,840 --> 00:37:06,950
Oh, my gosh.

825
00:37:07,010 --> 00:37:09,780
PICK ONE UP
AND TOP IT WITH WILD LETTUCE KIMCHI

826
00:37:10,720 --> 00:37:13,590
AND TAKE ONE GIANT BITE

827
00:37:13,650 --> 00:37:16,690
THAT'S WHAT I'M TALKING ABOUT

828
00:37:16,760 --> 00:37:19,120
- Do I eat it whole like that?
- Yes, the texture's better that way.

829
00:37:21,190 --> 00:37:25,500
HE EATS IT WHOLE IN ONE BITE
AS RAIN SAYS

830
00:37:25,560 --> 00:37:27,030
Today is seriously...

831
00:37:27,100 --> 00:37:34,670
IT'S THE DAY THE TRIO GETS SPOILED

832
00:37:35,070 --> 00:37:37,310
HAPPY

833
00:37:37,380 --> 00:37:38,440
It's still good.

834
00:37:39,380 --> 00:37:41,150
FEELING PROUD

835
00:37:41,210 --> 00:37:42,950
Where did you learn all this?

836
00:37:43,010 --> 00:37:45,320
No, we've always cooked
and eaten like this.

837
00:37:47,450 --> 00:37:49,320
- It's seriously good.
- Do you like it?

838
00:37:50,360 --> 00:37:52,460
- Thank you so much.
- Don't mention it.

839
00:37:53,990 --> 00:37:56,230
Tell me if you want more meat.

840
00:37:56,290 --> 00:37:57,930
- Okay.
- I'm fine.

841
00:37:59,430 --> 00:38:05,500
HOW ARE YOU SUPPOSED TO STOP EATING?

842
00:38:05,570 --> 00:38:06,870
LOOKING AROUND

843
00:38:06,940 --> 00:38:08,640
- Do you also have <i>ramyeon</i>?
- Yes.

844
00:38:08,710 --> 00:38:10,040
- We've got everything.
- Do you want it?

845
00:38:10,940 --> 00:38:12,310
Want me to cook it?

846
00:38:12,380 --> 00:38:13,850
A FULL COURSE WHICH INCLUDES <i>RAMYEON</i>

847
00:38:13,910 --> 00:38:15,310
It's all beef fat, so it's fine.

848
00:38:17,380 --> 00:38:21,720
COOKING <i>RAMYEON </i>IN THE VERY POT
THE MEAT WAS GRILLED IN

849
00:38:22,490 --> 00:38:24,920
I didn't know you liked cooking
and were good at it.

850
00:38:24,990 --> 00:38:26,930
There's nothing good about this.
You just throw it in.

851
00:38:30,100 --> 00:38:35,970
HE EVEN TOSSES IN <i>KIMCHI</i>
THAT BO GUM CHOPPED

852
00:38:37,840 --> 00:38:39,700
EYES LOCKED IN

853
00:38:39,770 --> 00:38:41,170
Good idea, Dong-yeon.

854
00:38:42,170 --> 00:38:44,210
- I'll put in a couple of cloves.
- Perfect.

855
00:38:44,280 --> 00:38:45,840
DONG-YEON INSTINCTIVELY MINCES GARLIC

856
00:38:46,310 --> 00:38:49,980
MINCED GARLIC GOES INTO THE <i>RAMYEON</i>

857
00:38:52,680 --> 00:38:55,420
STIR THE NOODLES AROUND A LITTLE

858
00:38:57,190 --> 00:39:00,860
- That looks insane.
- It suddenly became a masterpiece.

859
00:39:00,930 --> 00:39:03,060
I'll move it over there.

860
00:39:03,130 --> 00:39:05,660
IS HE MOVING IT INTO ANOTHER BOWL?

861
00:39:05,730 --> 00:39:07,800
- Come here.
- We can do this, right?

862
00:39:07,870 --> 00:39:09,800
- This is okay, right?
- Are you moving it there?

863
00:39:10,400 --> 00:39:12,340
- Why don't you move the whole pot?
- Let's set it down.

864
00:39:12,400 --> 00:39:13,940
- I'm scared.
- I should take it like this.

865
00:39:14,010 --> 00:39:15,670
- Yes.
- Yes, put it on top.

866
00:39:15,740 --> 00:39:16,910
- Like this?
- On top of this.

867
00:39:16,980 --> 00:39:18,580
- Is this better?
- Take the bottom one out.

868
00:39:18,640 --> 00:39:20,110
- I'm putting it on.
- Perfect.

869
00:39:20,180 --> 00:39:21,380
- That's good.
- It's stable.

870
00:39:22,450 --> 00:39:24,680
- Let's eat up.
- Seriously, this is...

871
00:39:24,750 --> 00:39:26,620
- You really have to eat now.
- Yes, let's eat.

872
00:39:27,490 --> 00:39:29,990
- It looks insane.
- It smells delicious.

873
00:39:30,060 --> 00:39:31,260
TIME FOR <i>RAMYEON</i>

874
00:39:31,320 --> 00:39:33,190
Amazing. This is pretty salty.

875
00:39:34,430 --> 00:39:38,560
THE NOODLES DISAPPEAR IN ONE SLURP

876
00:39:38,860 --> 00:39:40,800
THIS IS A BIT COLD

877
00:39:40,870 --> 00:39:42,000
EXCLAIMING

878
00:39:42,470 --> 00:39:43,900
The <i>ramyeon </i>is a masterpiece.

879
00:39:44,700 --> 00:39:47,370
- The heat needs to be high.
- Indeed.

880
00:39:47,440 --> 00:39:51,280
AFTER FEEDING THE TRIO MEAT,
HE FINALLY TAKES A BITE OF <i>RAMYEON</i>

881
00:39:55,350 --> 00:39:56,350
WHAT IS THIS?

882
00:39:56,410 --> 00:39:57,520
Good, right?

883
00:39:57,580 --> 00:39:58,920
IT'S A WORK OF ART, ISN'T IT?

884
00:39:58,980 --> 00:40:01,320
- This is cooked well.
- It's insane, right?

885
00:40:06,220 --> 00:40:07,360
This is awesome.

886
00:40:07,430 --> 00:40:08,660
HE SLURPS THE NOODLES NON-STOP

887
00:40:09,290 --> 00:40:12,030
NOW, THIS IS HAPPINESS

888
00:40:12,100 --> 00:40:14,470
I forced myself to stop because
I felt like I should quit eating.

889
00:40:14,530 --> 00:40:16,000
BO GUM EVEN MIXES IN RICE

890
00:40:16,070 --> 00:40:17,370
I'm about to lose my mind.

891
00:40:25,380 --> 00:40:27,110
ONE BITE OF MEAT FIRST

892
00:40:30,020 --> 00:40:33,820
THEN SLURPS THE <i>RAMYEON </i>IMMEDIATELY

893
00:40:33,890 --> 00:40:35,450
I wasn't going to eat any.

894
00:40:37,390 --> 00:40:38,620
I'll get you new ones.

895
00:40:38,690 --> 00:40:42,190
HE CAN'T STOP HIS CHOPSTICKS
AFTER TASTING IT

896
00:40:42,260 --> 00:40:44,630
I've never eaten <i>ramyeon</i>
cooked in a pot like this.

897
00:40:44,700 --> 00:40:46,560
Same, it's my first time
eating tray <i>ramyeon.</i>

898
00:40:46,630 --> 00:40:47,830
- Seriously?
- Yes.

899
00:40:47,900 --> 00:40:49,170
BO GUM probably

900
00:40:50,240 --> 00:40:52,000
never got to do it
because he was always busy.

901
00:40:53,570 --> 00:40:55,470
- I don't think I've gone camping.
- Really?

902
00:40:56,410 --> 00:40:58,340
That was an absolute piece of art.

903
00:40:58,410 --> 00:41:03,580
A HAPPY TIME SPENT
WITH PEOPLE THEY CARE ABOUT

904
00:41:03,820 --> 00:41:05,080
It would be a shame to waste...

905
00:41:06,120 --> 00:41:08,650
Should I prep some of what's left?

906
00:41:08,720 --> 00:41:09,990
PREPPING THE LEFTOVER MEAT
FOR THE TRIO

907
00:41:10,360 --> 00:41:12,160
I'm going home, anyway.

908
00:41:12,690 --> 00:41:15,260
- We laid out a blanket.
- No.

909
00:41:15,360 --> 00:41:17,960
I'm honestly so happy
that I got to cook for you.

910
00:41:18,030 --> 00:41:20,300
I had such a great time
being with you.

911
00:41:20,770 --> 00:41:22,130
RAIN?

912
00:41:22,200 --> 00:41:23,870
Shouldn't you wash up
and go to bed now?

913
00:41:24,640 --> 00:41:25,870
Already?

914
00:41:26,470 --> 00:41:29,470
Wash up and lie down.
It's time for bed. Tomorrow...

915
00:41:29,540 --> 00:41:31,580
- It's our day off tomorrow.
- Right?

916
00:41:31,640 --> 00:41:34,280
- Tonight's a party.
- Is that right?

917
00:41:34,980 --> 00:41:39,420
ANYWAY, THEY DECIDE TO PREP
AND STORE THE LEFTOVER MEAT

918
00:41:39,480 --> 00:41:40,650
Let's head in now

919
00:41:40,720 --> 00:41:42,020
- and clean up.
- Okay.

920
00:41:42,090 --> 00:41:44,020
TIME FOR THE PASSIONATE PART-TIMER
TO HEAD HOME

921
00:41:44,090 --> 00:41:45,690
Thank you so much
for the amazing meal.

922
00:41:45,760 --> 00:41:47,560
- It was nothing.
- Thank you so much.

923
00:41:47,630 --> 00:41:48,630
THE TRIO REALLY FEASTED TODAY

924
00:41:48,690 --> 00:41:51,060
- I had so much fun today.
- So did we.

925
00:41:51,130 --> 00:41:53,800
You know what's weird, though?

926
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:56,770
I think I'm going to miss
those ladies from today.

927
00:41:56,840 --> 00:41:58,140
I know.

928
00:41:58,670 --> 00:42:03,170
- Da-in, Ji-hui, and Seon-hui too.
- Seon-hui.

929
00:42:03,240 --> 00:42:05,410
- And their grandma.
- Take good care of them for me.

930
00:42:05,480 --> 00:42:08,080
- Yes.
- They looked so bored earlier.

931
00:42:09,350 --> 00:42:11,050
Seriously, thanks so much.

932
00:42:11,120 --> 00:42:12,750
Get inside.

933
00:42:12,820 --> 00:42:13,990
- Get home safe.
- Bye.

934
00:42:14,050 --> 00:42:15,390
- Thank you for coming.
- Sure.

935
00:42:15,450 --> 00:42:16,550
- See you.
- Sleep tight.

936
00:42:16,620 --> 00:42:17,620
- Thank you.
- Bye.

937
00:42:17,690 --> 00:42:19,390
- Watch your head.
- Okay.

938
00:42:19,460 --> 00:42:22,660
RAIN HEADS OFF AFTER WORKING
LIKE A ONE-PERSON ARMY

939
00:42:22,730 --> 00:42:24,460
- He's...
- Wait.

940
00:42:24,530 --> 00:42:26,100
- Bye, thank you.
- See you!

941
00:42:26,160 --> 00:42:27,770
SAYING GOODBYE OVER AND OVER AGAIN
RELUCTANT TO PART

942
00:42:27,830 --> 00:42:29,000
Bye, guys.

943
00:42:33,440 --> 00:42:35,540
THANK YOU FOR YOUR HELP

944
00:42:36,040 --> 00:42:38,540
THANKS TO RAIN, IT WAS SUCH A FUN DAY

945
00:42:39,780 --> 00:42:44,720
THE PASSIONATE PART-TIMER RAIN
HAS FINALLY LEFT

946
00:42:45,350 --> 00:42:49,590
10:00 P.M.

947
00:42:50,990 --> 00:42:54,260
BO GUM PULLS OUT A NOTEBOOK

948
00:42:54,690 --> 00:42:56,190
PLOPS DOWN

949
00:42:59,400 --> 00:43:02,570
HE STARTS WRITING SOMETHING

950
00:43:04,170 --> 00:43:07,870
THINKING

951
00:43:08,940 --> 00:43:12,540
DEEP IN THOUGHT

952
00:43:12,610 --> 00:43:18,020
WHAT COULD HE BE WRITING?

953
00:43:18,080 --> 00:43:20,650
A CUT FOR MR. KWON HYEON-SEOK

954
00:43:20,720 --> 00:43:26,160
HE'S ACTUALLY BEEN WRITING
A SALES LOG EVERY SINGLE DAY

955
00:43:26,590 --> 00:43:30,400
RECALLING THE PEOPLE
HE MET EACH DAY

956
00:43:31,800 --> 00:43:34,700
HE HAD BEEN RECORDING
EACH DAY AS IT HAPPENED

957
00:43:35,470 --> 00:43:37,370
A DAY OFF FOR THE FIRST TIME EVER

958
00:43:37,440 --> 00:43:40,670
AND TOMORROW IS A DAY FOR REGROUPING

959
00:43:41,270 --> 00:43:42,670
Are you writing in the log?

960
00:43:43,170 --> 00:43:44,180
Yes.

961
00:43:45,380 --> 00:43:47,350
PLEASED FOR SOME REASON

962
00:43:47,410 --> 00:43:49,750
I think I did a really good job
on everyone's hair today.

963
00:43:49,810 --> 00:43:51,180
Yes, they all turned out great.

964
00:43:51,780 --> 00:43:53,420
The guy's hair looked really good.

965
00:43:53,490 --> 00:43:54,690
<i>Hyeon-seok.</i>

966
00:43:55,250 --> 00:43:56,650
<i>Come on.</i>

967
00:43:57,020 --> 00:43:58,720
And Da-in's hair was pretty.

968
00:43:59,320 --> 00:44:00,860
Her hair looked so nice.

969
00:44:01,230 --> 00:44:04,130
THE BRACELET DA-IN GAVE HIM

970
00:44:04,200 --> 00:44:05,330
I'm so thankful.

971
00:44:06,430 --> 00:44:08,500
SOFT SMILE

972
00:44:09,570 --> 00:44:12,170
Whether it's Da-in,
Seon-hui, or Ji-hui

973
00:44:12,540 --> 00:44:13,770
ten years from now

974
00:44:14,040 --> 00:44:17,840
if I run into them somewhere
or if I come back to Muju...

975
00:44:19,140 --> 00:44:21,350
I want to see how they've changed.

976
00:44:21,710 --> 00:44:24,150
I'm really curious
what they'll be like

977
00:44:24,220 --> 00:44:26,120
in high school or in college

978
00:44:26,450 --> 00:44:30,160
and how capable they'll be
when they start working.

979
00:44:33,160 --> 00:44:37,100
THE PEOPLE THEY MET HERE
HAVE ALREADY BECOME PRECIOUS

980
00:44:42,030 --> 00:44:47,570
REPLAYING THE MEMORIES,
THE NIGHT SLOWLY GROWS DEEPER

981
00:44:48,770 --> 00:44:51,410
THE NEXT DAY

982
00:44:52,810 --> 00:44:56,950
THE FIRST AND LAST DAY OFF
FOR THE VILLAGE BARBER

983
00:44:57,850 --> 00:45:02,590
5:00 A.M.

984
00:45:03,990 --> 00:45:06,520
THE VILLAGE

985
00:45:06,590 --> 00:45:08,360
AND THE BARBERSHOP

986
00:45:08,430 --> 00:45:11,960
ARE BOTH QUIET

987
00:45:14,100 --> 00:45:15,330
TURNING ON

988
00:45:17,240 --> 00:45:21,340
SOMEONE'S AT THE BARBERSHOP
ON THEIR DAY OFF

989
00:45:22,310 --> 00:45:24,780
HE HEADS INTO THE KITCHEN

990
00:45:28,380 --> 00:45:31,380
AND PREPS INGREDIENTS

991
00:45:33,180 --> 00:45:35,320
THE ONE COOKING AT DAWN

992
00:45:35,390 --> 00:45:38,190
ON THEIR DAY OFF IS

993
00:45:40,590 --> 00:45:43,290
BO GUM

994
00:45:43,800 --> 00:45:46,860
THE FILLING HE MADE IN ADVANCE

995
00:45:47,470 --> 00:45:49,500
WHEN DID HE MAKE ALL THIS?

996
00:45:49,970 --> 00:45:52,540
4 HOURS EARLIER
AT 1:00 A.M.

997
00:45:53,070 --> 00:45:56,610
WITH HIS IRON STAMINA,
HE DIDN'T EVEN SLEEP MUCH

998
00:45:59,780 --> 00:46:04,850
HE HAD MADE SANDWICH FILLINGS
AHEAD OF TIME

999
00:46:06,220 --> 00:46:10,150
SINCE IT WAS THEIR DAY OFF,
HE STEPPED IN AS CHEF FOR DONG-YEON

1000
00:46:14,030 --> 00:46:17,730
BUT WHY SANDWICHES
THIS EARLY ON A DAY OFF?

1001
00:46:18,360 --> 00:46:21,300
5:30 A.M.

1002
00:46:21,370 --> 00:46:23,740
SANG-YI AND DONG-YEON ARE
ALSO UP EARLY

1003
00:46:23,800 --> 00:46:24,800
GOOD MORNING!

1004
00:46:24,870 --> 00:46:25,940
GOOD MORNING, SIR

1005
00:46:26,740 --> 00:46:27,940
YOU MAKING COFFEE?

1006
00:46:32,010 --> 00:46:33,750
Will it be cold?
Are you wearing thermal underwear?

1007
00:46:34,250 --> 00:46:36,480
I don't think it'll be that cold.

1008
00:46:37,020 --> 00:46:40,220
But who knows? It's a mountain.

1009
00:46:40,990 --> 00:46:43,120
- The temperature isn't that low.
- Really?

1010
00:46:45,420 --> 00:46:47,930
THE PRIDE OF MUJU

1011
00:46:47,990 --> 00:46:50,760
MOUNT DEOGYUSAN

1012
00:46:52,360 --> 00:46:56,000
ALTITUDE: 1,614M

1013
00:46:56,070 --> 00:46:59,340
THE FOURTH HIGHEST MOUNTAIN IN KOREA

1014
00:47:00,570 --> 00:47:02,910
ON THEIR PRECIOUS FIRST DAY OFF

1015
00:47:02,970 --> 00:47:07,080
THEY HEAD TO MOUNT DEOGYUSAN,
MUJU'S LANDMARK

1016
00:47:07,510 --> 00:47:09,050
BUT THEN!

1017
00:47:09,250 --> 00:47:12,520
<i>The longest and strongest cold wave</i>
<i>of the season is expected.</i>

1018
00:47:12,580 --> 00:47:14,690
WITH STRONG WINDS

1019
00:47:15,920 --> 00:47:19,420
AND HEAVY SNOW OVERNIGHT

1020
00:47:19,890 --> 00:47:22,590
WILL TODAY'S HIKE GO OKAY?

1021
00:47:23,730 --> 00:47:25,860
- Are you all ready?
- I'm ready.

1022
00:47:26,760 --> 00:47:29,670
Since we're heading out,
I'll turn this on.

1023
00:47:29,730 --> 00:47:31,870
- While we're gone...
- The robot vacuum.

1024
00:47:32,270 --> 00:47:33,540
It would be nice to clean the house.

1025
00:47:33,600 --> 00:47:34,710
- I'm pressing it.
- Yes.

1026
00:47:34,770 --> 00:47:37,380
THIS ROBOT VACUUM WILL WORK
FOR THE TRIO ON THEIR DAY OFF

1027
00:47:39,780 --> 00:47:42,510
It says it will clean
everything thoroughly through AI.

1028
00:47:42,580 --> 00:47:45,150
It'll go all over the place
to clean everything

1029
00:47:45,220 --> 00:47:46,880
- so let's trust it and head out.
- Let's go.

1030
00:47:49,490 --> 00:47:51,360
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

1031
00:47:51,420 --> 00:47:52,760
LET'S GO TO MOUNT DEOGYUSAN

1032
00:47:54,430 --> 00:47:55,690
The moon is still out.

1033
00:47:57,360 --> 00:47:59,600
I clipped my nails and tossed them,
and now it's up there.

1034
00:47:59,660 --> 00:48:01,800
- Did you throw that nail?
- Yes.

1035
00:48:01,870 --> 00:48:03,300
You should have asked me to cut it.

1036
00:48:04,470 --> 00:48:08,210
THE MOON SHAPED LIKE DONG-YEON'S NAIL
IS STILL BRIGHT IN THE SKY

1037
00:48:09,740 --> 00:48:11,540
THEY WALK PAST THE BARBERSHOP

1038
00:48:11,980 --> 00:48:13,910
<i>So nice and smooth, so smooth</i>

1039
00:48:13,980 --> 00:48:15,580
Do you remember...

1040
00:48:15,650 --> 00:48:17,980
- Since we're
- Yes?

1041
00:48:18,050 --> 00:48:20,520
not opening today,
shouldn't we leave a note?

1042
00:48:20,590 --> 00:48:22,290
We'll leave the lights on.

1043
00:48:22,350 --> 00:48:24,160
"Come rest."

1044
00:48:25,390 --> 00:48:28,530
"We are

1045
00:48:29,260 --> 00:48:34,470
closed today."

1046
00:48:34,700 --> 00:48:36,930
- "Even if we're not here."
- "Even if we're not here."

1047
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:38,070
"Feel free to come in and relax."

1048
00:48:38,140 --> 00:48:40,170
THEY LEAVE A NOTE
FOR ANY CUSTOMERS WHO MIGHT STOP BY

1049
00:48:40,240 --> 00:48:42,210
And then we'll leave the lights on.

1050
00:48:42,270 --> 00:48:44,780
- Anything else?
- All good.

1051
00:48:44,840 --> 00:48:45,940
Let's turn this.

1052
00:48:46,010 --> 00:48:47,380
Mark it "Closed."

1053
00:48:47,910 --> 00:48:50,520
No, let's leave it at "open."
This place is always open.

1054
00:48:52,150 --> 00:48:53,720
Let's just turn that one off.

1055
00:48:54,250 --> 00:48:55,450
Yes, let's do that.

1056
00:48:55,890 --> 00:48:57,020
Perfect.

1057
00:48:57,090 --> 00:48:58,620
CLOSED ON TUESDAYS
WE'RE CLOSED TODAY

1058
00:48:58,690 --> 00:49:00,160
BUT FEEL FREE
TO COME IN AND RELAX

1059
00:49:00,930 --> 00:49:05,860
THE SHOP IS LEFT
WITH THE LIGHTS ON AND THE DOOR OPEN

1060
00:49:06,460 --> 00:49:11,140
THEIR WAY OF SAYING
ANYONE IS WELCOME

1061
00:49:11,540 --> 00:49:14,640
<i>Let's get out of here</i>

1062
00:49:14,710 --> 00:49:16,410
<i>Hey</i>

1063
00:49:16,470 --> 00:49:19,040
<i>To the mountain</i>

1064
00:49:20,240 --> 00:49:21,850
<i>Let's go!</i>

1065
00:49:21,910 --> 00:49:22,950
OFF TO MOUNT DEOGYUSAN AT 6:30 A.M.

1066
00:49:23,010 --> 00:49:24,420
<i>Let's go to Mount Deogyusan.</i>

1067
00:49:24,480 --> 00:49:26,180
<i>This kind of road always</i>
<i>makes me feel good.</i>

1068
00:49:27,620 --> 00:49:29,820
<i>I made egg mayo sandwiches.</i>

1069
00:49:30,890 --> 00:49:32,720
YUM

1070
00:49:34,360 --> 00:49:36,460
It's so good.

1071
00:49:36,960 --> 00:49:38,430
Isn't it a bit bland?

1072
00:49:38,500 --> 00:49:41,070
- No, it's perfectly seasoned.
- That's a relief.

1073
00:49:41,130 --> 00:49:42,870
CHEF KWAK APPROVES

1074
00:49:43,230 --> 00:49:44,300
SANG-YI ALSO GETS A SANDWICH

1075
00:49:44,370 --> 00:49:46,140
- Thank you so much.
- I just hope it tastes good.

1076
00:49:46,200 --> 00:49:47,610
When did you make these, though?

1077
00:49:48,210 --> 00:49:51,110
- In the morning.
- So, that's why you went there.

1078
00:49:51,280 --> 00:49:53,310
- The bread...
- You're seriously so thoughtful.

1079
00:49:55,180 --> 00:49:57,620
A BIG BITE

1080
00:50:01,420 --> 00:50:02,520
It's good.

1081
00:50:03,690 --> 00:50:05,290
It tastes healthy, right?

1082
00:50:06,290 --> 00:50:10,290
BO GUM'S EGG MAYO SANDWICHES ARE
HEALTHY AND DELICIOUS

1083
00:50:10,360 --> 00:50:12,160
It was really good.

1084
00:50:14,070 --> 00:50:16,570
SANG-YI GETS PLEASANTLY DROWSY
AFTER THE SANDWICH

1085
00:50:16,630 --> 00:50:17,870
It's our first day off.

1086
00:50:19,540 --> 00:50:21,370
<i>- We are</i>
<i>- Going on a</i>

1087
00:50:21,440 --> 00:50:22,510
<i>Trip</i>

1088
00:50:22,870 --> 00:50:24,640
- That's...
- I went along with it

1089
00:50:24,710 --> 00:50:25,880
but was that the right tune?

1090
00:50:26,310 --> 00:50:27,650
Was that what you were trying to do?

1091
00:50:29,350 --> 00:50:31,620
<i>It's such an incredible view.</i>

1092
00:50:32,380 --> 00:50:34,390
<i>There's still snow</i>
<i>up on the mountains.</i>

1093
00:50:34,450 --> 00:50:35,550
MOUNT DEOGYUSAN STARTS
COMING INTO VIEW

1094
00:50:35,620 --> 00:50:37,050
<i>My gosh, let's hurry.</i>

1095
00:50:37,120 --> 00:50:38,190
<i>Hurry?</i>

1096
00:50:40,760 --> 00:50:42,390
<i>- It's so pretty.</i>
<i>- It's still</i>

1097
00:50:42,460 --> 00:50:44,200
<i>- winter here.</i>
<i>- What is this?</i>

1098
00:50:44,260 --> 00:50:45,600
- What?
- What?

1099
00:50:45,660 --> 00:50:46,860
This resort is so nice.

1100
00:50:46,930 --> 00:50:48,170
It feels like another country.

1101
00:50:48,230 --> 00:50:50,230
It would make a great filming site.

1102
00:50:50,300 --> 00:50:52,300
- Well, we are filming.
- Oh, you're right.

1103
00:50:52,370 --> 00:50:53,640
That's why we're here.

1104
00:50:54,470 --> 00:50:57,040
LAUGHING

1105
00:50:57,110 --> 00:50:58,810
<i>I have arrived.</i>

1106
00:50:59,410 --> 00:51:02,710
<i>- We're here!</i>
<i>- We're here!</i>

1107
00:51:02,780 --> 00:51:03,780
THE FOOT OF MOUNT DEOGYUSAN

1108
00:51:05,750 --> 00:51:06,920
Hold on.

1109
00:51:07,420 --> 00:51:09,120
The wind feels a little weird.

1110
00:51:09,720 --> 00:51:11,190
Are you wearing thermal underwear?

1111
00:51:11,260 --> 00:51:12,920
- No.
- Me neither.

1112
00:51:12,990 --> 00:51:14,830
It's too chilly, though.

1113
00:51:14,890 --> 00:51:17,130
It's too cold. The wind is no joke.

1114
00:51:17,190 --> 00:51:18,960
- Do your gloves feel warm?
- Yes.

1115
00:51:19,030 --> 00:51:20,100
IT FEELS LIKE MINUS 15 DEGREES

1116
00:51:20,160 --> 00:51:21,530
It's a ski resort!

1117
00:51:21,600 --> 00:51:24,200
This is probably my first time
at a ski resort in 15 years.

1118
00:51:25,540 --> 00:51:28,610
THEIR FIRST OUTING AFTER A WHILE

1119
00:51:28,670 --> 00:51:31,140
THEY FORGET ABOUT THE COLD
AND GET EXCITED

1120
00:51:31,310 --> 00:51:32,810
It looks so fun.

1121
00:51:33,540 --> 00:51:35,510
Can we look at the sign for a second?

1122
00:51:35,580 --> 00:51:36,680
Just a second?

1123
00:51:38,480 --> 00:51:40,890
TODAY'S HIKING ROUTE

1124
00:51:40,950 --> 00:51:41,990
GONDOLA STATION

1125
00:51:42,050 --> 00:51:43,650
<i>We take the gondola here.</i>

1126
00:51:45,790 --> 00:51:47,790
<i>We're going to Sangjeru Pavilion,</i>
<i>then Seolcheonbong Peak.</i>

1127
00:51:48,690 --> 00:51:50,460
<i>It's a little farther up from there.</i>

1128
00:51:50,530 --> 00:51:52,960
JUNGBONG PEAK, 1,594M, 1.6KM AWAY

1129
00:51:53,230 --> 00:51:55,500
<i>I can't remember the last time</i>
<i>I rode a gondola.</i>

1130
00:51:55,570 --> 00:51:57,170
<i>I'm so excited.</i>

1131
00:51:57,230 --> 00:51:58,940
<i>I can't believe</i>
<i>I'm on Mount Deogyusan.</i>

1132
00:52:01,010 --> 00:52:02,110
It's moving.

1133
00:52:03,110 --> 00:52:05,780
We have to get on it.
It's moving, guys.

1134
00:52:05,840 --> 00:52:07,580
TAKING A SELFIE AS HE'S EXCITED
ON THE WAY TO THE GONDOLA

1135
00:52:08,050 --> 00:52:09,250
Hop in.

1136
00:52:09,310 --> 00:52:10,880
- You first.
- Okay.

1137
00:52:10,950 --> 00:52:12,650
- You first.
- I'll go first.

1138
00:52:12,720 --> 00:52:14,090
THRILLED

1139
00:52:15,020 --> 00:52:17,390
- Ouch, that hurts.
- What?

1140
00:52:17,460 --> 00:52:18,720
- Are you okay?
- That hurts.

1141
00:52:18,790 --> 00:52:19,920
That hurts so bad.

1142
00:52:19,990 --> 00:52:21,730
HIT HIS HEAD ON THE GONDOLA

1143
00:52:22,590 --> 00:52:23,790
- Are you okay?
- Yes.

1144
00:52:24,930 --> 00:52:26,300
There's no seatbelt, right?

1145
00:52:26,360 --> 00:52:28,330
No, and my butt is really cold.

1146
00:52:28,900 --> 00:52:29,900
ONE HOUR LATER

1147
00:52:29,970 --> 00:52:31,600
<i>I feel like we're stranded.</i>

1148
00:52:31,940 --> 00:52:32,940
SCREAMING

1149
00:52:33,540 --> 00:52:34,910
My legs are sinking!

1150
00:52:34,970 --> 00:52:36,370
WIND AND SNOWSTORM ATTACK

1151
00:52:36,470 --> 00:52:37,640
Watch out, guys!

1152
00:52:37,710 --> 00:52:39,280
<i>Grab this as you climb up!</i>

1153
00:52:41,550 --> 00:52:42,810
<i>I'm okay.</i>

1154
00:52:43,780 --> 00:52:44,980
<i>Sang-yi!</i>

1155
00:52:45,950 --> 00:52:46,950
<i>Help us.</i>

1156
00:52:47,020 --> 00:52:48,020
WHAT WILL HAPPEN TO THEM?

1157
00:52:48,090 --> 00:52:49,090
<i>Please save us.</i>

1158
00:52:50,390 --> 00:52:53,220
- It's going higher than I expected.
- I know, right?

1159
00:52:53,620 --> 00:52:56,130
None of the snow melted up here.

1160
00:52:57,160 --> 00:52:59,160
- It's beautiful.
- Right?

1161
00:53:00,630 --> 00:53:01,930
We're actually on a trip.

1162
00:53:03,070 --> 00:53:04,740
This place is incredible.

1163
00:53:06,470 --> 00:53:07,610
I think we're almost there.

1164
00:53:08,340 --> 00:53:09,970
Let's get ready to get off.

1165
00:53:12,110 --> 00:53:17,310
TIME TO FINALLY SEE
THE SNOWY SCENERY UP CLOSE

1166
00:53:18,220 --> 00:53:19,250
EXCLAIMING

1167
00:53:19,320 --> 00:53:21,020
Everything's frozen.

1168
00:53:21,820 --> 00:53:25,060
ONCE THEY STEP
OUT OF THE GONDOLA STATION

1169
00:53:25,860 --> 00:53:29,230
THE ROOF IS FROZEN

1170
00:53:29,290 --> 00:53:32,660
AND SO ARE THE SIGNS

1171
00:53:33,160 --> 00:53:36,400
THEY ARRIVE AT SEOLCHEONBONG PEAK
WHERE THEY CAN'T SEE A THING

1172
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:39,670
ON A CLEAR DAY,
SEOLCHEONBONG PEAK LOOKS LIKE THIS

1173
00:53:39,740 --> 00:53:42,610
AN ARCHIVAL FOOTAGE

1174
00:53:43,410 --> 00:53:47,080
BUT NOW, THEY CAN'T SEE A FOOT AHEAD

1175
00:53:47,550 --> 00:53:48,780
Unbelievable.

1176
00:53:49,880 --> 00:53:52,050
CAN WE REALLY HIKE?

1177
00:53:52,620 --> 00:53:54,520
- This feels so good, though.
- Yes.

1178
00:53:55,220 --> 00:53:56,950
RUSHING

1179
00:53:57,490 --> 00:53:58,690
SANG-YI IS RUNNING

1180
00:53:58,760 --> 00:54:02,160
HE SPRINTS AHEAD LIKE A PUPPY
STEPPING ON SNOW FOR THE FIRST TIME

1181
00:54:02,230 --> 00:54:03,390
Wait...

1182
00:54:03,860 --> 00:54:05,260
Calm down.

1183
00:54:06,230 --> 00:54:07,260
SANG-YI RUNS OFF

1184
00:54:07,330 --> 00:54:09,100
EXCITED

1185
00:54:09,170 --> 00:54:10,230
Wait...

1186
00:54:11,270 --> 00:54:13,800
My legs are sinking!

1187
00:54:14,810 --> 00:54:16,710
SINKING

1188
00:54:18,440 --> 00:54:19,980
Hold on.

1189
00:54:20,040 --> 00:54:21,450
INHALING SHARPLY

1190
00:54:22,050 --> 00:54:23,610
It's too cold.

1191
00:54:24,880 --> 00:54:26,450
What do I do?

1192
00:54:27,120 --> 00:54:28,420
Hang on.

1193
00:54:28,490 --> 00:54:31,720
IT FEELS LIKE MINUS 15 DEGREES HERE
GUMDONGYI'S LOCATION

1194
00:54:31,790 --> 00:54:34,060
This is no joke.

1195
00:54:34,130 --> 00:54:36,160
- I've never been in this thick snow.
- Me neither.

1196
00:54:37,560 --> 00:54:38,960
Isn't this something you'd see

1197
00:54:39,030 --> 00:54:40,030
- in Northern Europe?
- I agree.

1198
00:54:40,100 --> 00:54:42,000
IT'S HARD TO BELIEVE
THIS IS A MOUNTAIN IN KOREA

1199
00:54:42,070 --> 00:54:43,300
I might get blown away.

1200
00:54:44,500 --> 00:54:46,400
I need to put my hood on.

1201
00:54:47,440 --> 00:54:49,410
THE COLD HITS
BEFORE THE HIKE HAS EVEN STARTED

1202
00:54:50,010 --> 00:54:53,710
THEY BUNDLE UP TIGHT WITH THEIR HOODS

1203
00:54:55,880 --> 00:54:57,310
- All right.
- Let's go.

1204
00:54:57,380 --> 00:55:00,450
THEY OFFICIALLY BEGIN THEIR HIKE

1205
00:55:01,350 --> 00:55:05,120
THEY'RE MET WITH BRUTAL WIND
FROM THE VERY START

1206
00:55:06,120 --> 00:55:07,360
It's steep.

1207
00:55:07,420 --> 00:55:09,130
AND A STEEP PATH COVERED IN SNOW

1208
00:55:09,930 --> 00:55:11,100
It's steeper than I thought.

1209
00:55:13,400 --> 00:55:17,870
THEY BOLDLY CAME HIKING
AS A TEAM BONDING TRIP ON A DAY OFF

1210
00:55:18,600 --> 00:55:20,370
THEY CLIMB

1211
00:55:20,440 --> 00:55:21,740
AND CLIMB UP THE STAIRS

1212
00:55:21,810 --> 00:55:22,870
PANTING

1213
00:55:24,310 --> 00:55:26,710
AN EARLY-MORNING CLIMB
AFTER WORK THE DAY BEFORE

1214
00:55:26,780 --> 00:55:28,380
THEY'RE SUDDENLY DRAINED

1215
00:55:29,150 --> 00:55:32,420
THE WIND ONLY GETS STRONGER

1216
00:55:33,220 --> 00:55:36,820
THEIR FIRST BREAK IS
MUCH HARSHER THAN EXPECTED

1217
00:55:37,450 --> 00:55:41,590
SUFFERING ON THEIR PRECIOUS DAY OFF

1218
00:55:42,630 --> 00:55:47,200
THE ICY WIND CUTS
STRAIGHT TO THE BONE

1219
00:55:47,260 --> 00:55:48,870
My nostrils are already frozen.

1220
00:55:49,330 --> 00:55:50,800
Seriously, my nostrils...

1221
00:55:52,740 --> 00:55:54,870
- My face is freezing.
- I know.

1222
00:55:54,940 --> 00:55:56,070
Hold on.

1223
00:55:56,140 --> 00:55:58,210
- My mouth is freezing.
- Right?

1224
00:55:58,280 --> 00:55:59,910
My nose and mouth are both frozen.

1225
00:56:01,450 --> 00:56:06,880
EVEN THE STAIRS AND HANDRAILS ARE
FROZEN IN THIS BRUTAL COLD

1226
00:56:08,090 --> 00:56:09,620
More than anything right now

1227
00:56:10,490 --> 00:56:13,960
I'm craving a cup of hot cocoa.

1228
00:56:14,260 --> 00:56:15,290
Let's get some.

1229
00:56:15,760 --> 00:56:17,190
Let's get hot cocoa, Dong-yeon.

1230
00:56:18,030 --> 00:56:20,260
BREATHING HEAVILY

1231
00:56:21,030 --> 00:56:22,900
- Do you want hot cocoa?
- Yes.

1232
00:56:24,100 --> 00:56:25,240
Just one cup.

1233
00:56:26,600 --> 00:56:31,040
WHILE THE TRIO BATTLES THE COLD

1234
00:56:32,380 --> 00:56:35,650
AT THE SAME TIME

1235
00:56:39,450 --> 00:56:43,390
THE BARBERSHOP THEY LEFT BEHIND
WITHOUT AN OWNER

1236
00:56:44,050 --> 00:56:46,290
IS WRAPPED IN WARM SUNSHINE

1237
00:56:47,390 --> 00:56:53,130
THE SUNLIGHT FEELS ESPECIALLY WARM
AT THE SHOP TODAY

1238
00:56:54,530 --> 00:56:59,440
WILL PEOPLE COME BY ON A DAY OFF,
JUST AS GUMDONGYI HOPED?

1239
00:57:00,040 --> 00:57:03,310
THE BARBERSHOP YARD IS
QUIET AND PEACEFUL

1240
00:57:06,940 --> 00:57:09,150
CUSTOMERS?

1241
00:57:09,210 --> 00:57:10,710
Haircuts are 5,000 won.

1242
00:57:11,680 --> 00:57:13,220
Looks like they're closed today.

1243
00:57:13,280 --> 00:57:14,890
"Today is our day off.

1244
00:57:14,950 --> 00:57:17,550
Even if we're not here,
feel free to come in and rest."

1245
00:57:18,590 --> 00:57:19,890
Let's head in.

1246
00:57:20,560 --> 00:57:23,460
We'll have a cup of coffee.
It's cold out.

1247
00:57:24,960 --> 00:57:26,860
<i>It's literally a reception room.</i>

1248
00:57:26,930 --> 00:57:29,000
THEY SIT AROUND CHATTING

1249
00:57:31,700 --> 00:57:35,440
ANOTHER VISITOR TO THE BARBERSHOP IS

1250
00:57:36,240 --> 00:57:39,510
BUSY CHECKING HIS APPEARANCE

1251
00:57:39,580 --> 00:57:43,510
THE VILLAGE CHIEF

1252
00:57:45,520 --> 00:57:47,450
Cleaning never ends.

1253
00:57:47,520 --> 00:57:51,660
HE CLEANS THE BARBERSHOP FOR THE TRIO

1254
00:57:56,790 --> 00:58:02,000
MS. OU ALSO VISITS
AND HELPS HERSELF TO SOME SNACKS

1255
00:58:04,640 --> 00:58:11,480
EACH VILLAGER SPENDS TIME
AT THE SHOP IN THEIR OWN WAY

1256
00:58:12,910 --> 00:58:14,040
COFFEE IN ONE HAND,
BREAD IN THE OTHER

1257
00:58:14,110 --> 00:58:15,450
It's warm.

1258
00:58:15,510 --> 00:58:16,880
Oh, it's warm.

1259
00:58:19,650 --> 00:58:22,250
SIPPING

1260
00:58:23,220 --> 00:58:27,960
THIS IS MS.OU'S PERSONAL CAFE

1261
00:58:29,260 --> 00:58:32,030
RELAXED

1262
00:58:32,100 --> 00:58:33,460
It's hot.

1263
00:58:33,530 --> 00:58:36,100
WHILE MS. OU ENJOYS HER COFFEE

1264
00:58:36,170 --> 00:58:37,330
GROANING

1265
00:58:45,240 --> 00:58:49,780
1 HOUR INTO THE FREEZING HIKE

1266
00:58:51,820 --> 00:58:53,220
PANTING

1267
00:58:53,280 --> 00:58:55,690
GROANING

1268
00:58:56,650 --> 00:59:00,160
BOSS PARK WITH IRON STAMINA IS
JUST HAVING A BLAST

1269
00:59:00,220 --> 00:59:01,930
HUMMING

1270
00:59:01,990 --> 00:59:03,960
<i>It's even more exciting and fun</i>

1271
00:59:04,030 --> 00:59:05,800
<i>because it's my first time</i>
<i>climbing a snowy mountain.</i>

1272
00:59:05,860 --> 00:59:08,000
SANG-YI PANTING

1273
00:59:08,700 --> 00:59:11,070
ONE, TWO

1274
00:59:11,770 --> 00:59:13,340
LED BY BOSS PARK,
THEY PUSH TOWARD JUNGBONG PEAK

1275
00:59:13,400 --> 00:59:14,570
GRUNT

1276
00:59:14,640 --> 00:59:15,710
WHAT?

1277
00:59:15,770 --> 00:59:16,910
GRUNT

1278
00:59:17,470 --> 00:59:20,580
THE UPHILL TRAIL
STRETCHES ON ENDLESSLY

1279
00:59:21,350 --> 00:59:24,980
AND THE EMPLOYEES' BREATHING
GETS HEAVIER AND HEAVIER

1280
00:59:25,450 --> 00:59:27,950
Left foot.

1281
00:59:28,320 --> 00:59:30,490
Left foot.

1282
00:59:30,950 --> 00:59:33,460
MEANWHILE, BOSS PARK SHOWS
NO SIGN OF TIRING

1283
00:59:33,520 --> 00:59:35,030
This place feels

1284
00:59:35,090 --> 00:59:37,730
like it has a little bit
of different regions in it.

1285
00:59:38,130 --> 00:59:40,560
It kind of feels like New Zealand.

1286
00:59:42,030 --> 00:59:43,500
It feels amazing.

1287
00:59:45,570 --> 00:59:47,600
<i>Into the unknown</i>

1288
00:59:48,740 --> 00:59:50,970
EXCITEMENT LEVEL MAX

1289
00:59:52,540 --> 00:59:53,780
Hello.

1290
00:59:53,840 --> 00:59:56,510
THE EXHAUSTED EMPLOYEES
AND THE OVEREXCITED BOSS

1291
00:59:58,450 --> 01:00:03,720
BOSS, WE'RE NOT IN THE MOOD TO SMILE

1292
01:00:04,350 --> 01:00:06,260
IS EVERYONE COMING OKAY?

1293
01:00:06,320 --> 01:00:08,690
- I'll take a picture for you.
- I'm fine.

1294
01:00:09,560 --> 01:00:12,130
PANTING

1295
01:00:12,430 --> 01:00:14,060
- Are you keeping up, Dong-yeon?
- Yes.

1296
01:00:15,030 --> 01:00:16,230
Cocoa.

1297
01:00:16,300 --> 01:00:18,500
I'M CLIMBING
WHILE THINKING ONLY ABOUT HOT COCOA

1298
01:00:19,440 --> 01:00:21,000
HE TURNS AROUND AGAIN

1299
01:00:21,070 --> 01:00:23,710
EMPTY

1300
01:00:24,340 --> 01:00:26,480
SHOWS UP

1301
01:00:27,210 --> 01:00:30,610
ALL YOU CAN HEAR IS
THEIR HEAVY BREATHING

1302
01:00:31,250 --> 01:00:33,850
IT'S STILL A LONELY HIKE
THOUGH THEY'RE TOGETHER

1303
01:00:34,650 --> 01:00:36,550
WE'RE COMING, BOSS

1304
01:00:36,620 --> 01:00:39,190
BREATHING HEAVILY

1305
01:00:40,090 --> 01:00:41,860
Dong-yeon, put your hood on.

1306
01:00:41,930 --> 01:00:44,430
THE SNOWSTORM GROWS EVEN FIERCER

1307
01:00:45,030 --> 01:00:46,060
Hold up.

1308
01:00:46,130 --> 01:00:48,330
It got colder than earlier!

1309
01:00:48,900 --> 01:00:50,500
Watch out, guys!

1310
01:00:51,240 --> 01:00:53,240
THE WIND IS SO STRONG
THAT IT'S HARD TO KEEP THEIR BALANCE

1311
01:00:53,300 --> 01:00:55,770
It's getting way too tough now.

1312
01:00:56,140 --> 01:00:58,640
AND BO GUM IS STILL CHEERFUL

1313
01:00:58,710 --> 01:01:00,040
Wait.

1314
01:01:00,110 --> 01:01:03,780
IT'S TOTAL CHAOS HERE

1315
01:01:04,880 --> 01:01:08,990
THE CLOSER THEY GET TO JUNGBONG PEAK,
THE STRONGER THE WIND GETS

1316
01:01:10,920 --> 01:01:12,420
I see the summit up there.

1317
01:01:13,490 --> 01:01:15,360
I see the lookout platform.

1318
01:01:15,430 --> 01:01:16,630
Are we already here?

1319
01:01:17,460 --> 01:01:18,530
Man.

1320
01:01:19,360 --> 01:01:22,570
I made it here,
all thanks to Dong-yeon and Sang-yi.

1321
01:01:22,870 --> 01:01:24,430
No, we made it here, thanks to you.

1322
01:01:25,640 --> 01:01:27,970
- Thanks.
- Thank you.

1323
01:01:28,140 --> 01:01:29,340
I mean it.

1324
01:01:29,910 --> 01:01:32,280
IS SANG-YI KEEPING UP OKAY?

1325
01:01:33,040 --> 01:01:36,680
SQUEEZING OUT
THE LAST OF HIS STRENGTH

1326
01:01:37,850 --> 01:01:42,420
THEY REACH JUNGBONG PEAK
AFTER 1 HOUR AND 30 MINUTES

1327
01:01:42,890 --> 01:01:45,990
JUNGBONG PEAK, 1,594M

1328
01:01:46,690 --> 01:01:49,030
- My gosh, what even is this?
- Oh, my.

1329
01:01:49,090 --> 01:01:50,860
WHAT KIND OF VIEW AWAITS THEM
FROM JUNGBONG PEAK?

1330
01:01:50,930 --> 01:01:53,100
IMPRESSED

1331
01:01:54,130 --> 01:01:55,430
This is no joke.

1332
01:01:59,840 --> 01:02:01,100
What's wrong?

1333
01:02:01,170 --> 01:02:04,810
NOTHING BUT A WHITE BLUR
OF BLOWING SNOW

1334
01:02:06,440 --> 01:02:08,150
THEY WOULD'VE SEEN THE RIDGELINE
OF MOUNT DEOGYUSAN ON A CLEAR DAY

1335
01:02:08,210 --> 01:02:11,050
ARCHIVAL FOOTAGE

1336
01:02:11,110 --> 01:02:14,450
BUT INSTEAD

1337
01:02:16,290 --> 01:02:20,460
ALL THEY CAN SEE IS
A WHITE WALL OF SNOW

1338
01:02:20,520 --> 01:02:22,630
Let's shout out.

1339
01:02:22,690 --> 01:02:23,830
In 1, 2, 3.

1340
01:02:23,890 --> 01:02:27,200
FORCED ENERGY

1341
01:02:27,260 --> 01:02:29,770
BOUNCING

1342
01:02:29,830 --> 01:02:32,140
Thanks for playing along.

1343
01:02:32,800 --> 01:02:33,800
SIGHING

1344
01:02:34,940 --> 01:02:35,970
Sang-yi.

1345
01:02:36,340 --> 01:02:38,740
Sang-yi, your hair.

1346
01:02:39,940 --> 01:02:41,180
Your hair...

1347
01:02:41,710 --> 01:02:42,910
Sang-yi!

1348
01:02:46,220 --> 01:02:49,650
HIS HAIR HAS TURNED WHITE AND GRAY

1349
01:02:50,450 --> 01:02:53,490
AND HIS EYES HAVE GONE BLANK

1350
01:02:53,560 --> 01:02:54,860
Sang-yi!

1351
01:02:55,290 --> 01:02:58,060
Wake up. We're almost there!

1352
01:02:58,730 --> 01:02:59,930
Are you going to give up now?

1353
01:03:00,500 --> 01:03:03,530
Are you going to quit
and let it all go?

1354
01:03:03,600 --> 01:03:04,640
Go on first.

1355
01:03:04,700 --> 01:03:06,900
No, I won't go without you.

1356
01:03:07,200 --> 01:03:09,640
Open your eyes!

1357
01:03:09,710 --> 01:03:11,040
SANG-YI OPENS HIS EYES

1358
01:03:11,110 --> 01:03:12,580
Nail art.

1359
01:03:12,640 --> 01:03:14,240
I have to go and do nail art.

1360
01:03:15,080 --> 01:03:16,180
STILL PROFESSIONAL ON A DAY OFF

1361
01:03:16,250 --> 01:03:17,450
I have to go do nail art.

1362
01:03:18,180 --> 01:03:19,420
Ma'am!

1363
01:03:20,450 --> 01:03:21,990
I have to fix Ms. Ra's nails.

1364
01:03:24,820 --> 01:03:26,060
Should we eat a tangerine?

1365
01:03:26,520 --> 01:03:27,520
A tangerine?

1366
01:03:27,590 --> 01:03:28,590
HERE?

1367
01:03:28,660 --> 01:03:29,660
- Where is it?
- I'll get it.

1368
01:03:29,730 --> 01:03:31,090
- Is it here?
- Turn around.

1369
01:03:31,730 --> 01:03:33,130
I also brought green grapes.

1370
01:03:33,730 --> 01:03:34,770
Would that be too cold?

1371
01:03:34,830 --> 01:03:36,670
Yes, I'm not eating those.

1372
01:03:39,100 --> 01:03:40,740
Tangerines.

1373
01:03:42,340 --> 01:03:44,410
AWARD-WORTHY ACTING

1374
01:03:44,470 --> 01:03:46,010
Let me get a piece.

1375
01:03:48,250 --> 01:03:49,450
It's warm.

1376
01:03:51,080 --> 01:03:52,150
I don't need this.

1377
01:03:52,220 --> 01:03:53,750
- Are you okay?
- You have to eat it.

1378
01:03:53,820 --> 01:03:54,820
Go ahead and eat it.

1379
01:03:55,820 --> 01:03:59,690
THEY DESPERATELY FILL
THEIR HUNGRY STOMACHS

1380
01:03:59,760 --> 01:04:02,690
THE SNOWSTORM GETS WORSE

1381
01:04:04,030 --> 01:04:05,800
I'll let you have them.

1382
01:04:08,330 --> 01:04:09,670
It's so cold.

1383
01:04:10,770 --> 01:04:11,940
My jaw won't move.

1384
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:13,370
PASSION FOR ACTING IS USELESS
AGAINST A COLD TANGERINE

1385
01:04:13,600 --> 01:04:14,810
It's so cold.

1386
01:04:15,540 --> 01:04:16,910
But it's good.

1387
01:04:16,970 --> 01:04:18,740
SNIFFLING

1388
01:04:19,210 --> 01:04:20,510
Let's go now.

1389
01:04:20,580 --> 01:04:22,080
We have to head back down.

1390
01:04:23,580 --> 01:04:24,950
I've got nail art to do.

1391
01:04:28,390 --> 01:04:29,690
It's freezing.

1392
01:04:31,920 --> 01:04:33,860
A SUSPICIOUS MAN SUDDENLY APPEARS

1393
01:04:35,860 --> 01:04:38,960
YOU CAN TELL HE'S BIG
EVEN FROM FAR AWAY

1394
01:04:40,330 --> 01:04:44,300
HE LOOKS AROUND
LIKE HE'S NEVER BEEN HERE BEFORE

1395
01:04:45,100 --> 01:04:48,670
THIS MYSTERIOUS MAN IS

1396
01:04:49,670 --> 01:04:53,880
YOON NAM-NO, THE FOODIE CHEF

1397
01:04:54,440 --> 01:04:57,180
<i>I heard the three actors were</i>
<i>working really hard.</i>

1398
01:04:57,780 --> 01:05:02,190
<i>So I came with one simple thought</i>
<i>that I wanted to cook them a meal.</i>

1399
01:05:02,250 --> 01:05:03,520
A TRAVELING CHEF
WHO CAME FOR GUMDONGYI

1400
01:05:04,150 --> 01:05:07,460
AND CHEF KWAK'S COOKING MENTOR

1401
01:05:08,790 --> 01:05:11,660
JEONG-JA, THEIR NEXT-DOOR NEIGHBOR,
COMES OUT OF THE COMMUNITY CENTER

1402
01:05:15,370 --> 01:05:17,570
- Are you going that way?
- Pardon?

1403
01:05:17,630 --> 01:05:19,170
Hello, ma'am.

1404
01:05:19,240 --> 01:05:21,640
Do you know where the barbershop is?

1405
01:05:21,710 --> 01:05:23,040
Yes.

1406
01:05:23,110 --> 01:05:25,440
BO GUM's...

1407
01:05:25,510 --> 01:05:27,340
- It's a secret.
- A secret?

1408
01:05:27,410 --> 01:05:29,080
- Don't tell anyone.
- Okay.

1409
01:05:29,710 --> 01:05:31,520
Follow me.

1410
01:05:31,580 --> 01:05:33,250
It's right next to my house.

1411
01:05:33,720 --> 01:05:35,250
- That way.
- That way?

1412
01:05:35,320 --> 01:05:36,620
NEXT-DOOR GUIDE JEONG-JA
LEADS THE WAY

1413
01:05:36,690 --> 01:05:38,160
Since it's your first time here.

1414
01:05:39,990 --> 01:05:41,360
The air is fresh.

1415
01:05:41,430 --> 01:05:42,860
It is fresh.

1416
01:05:42,930 --> 01:05:44,090
THEY GET ALONG
DESPITE THEIR FIRST ENCOUNTER

1417
01:05:44,160 --> 01:05:45,300
This is it.

1418
01:05:45,360 --> 01:05:46,560
- Here?
- The actor's shop.

1419
01:05:48,970 --> 01:05:51,330
Oh, here it is, The Village Barber.

1420
01:05:52,040 --> 01:05:53,770
It looks nice.
They did a great job with it.

1421
01:05:53,840 --> 01:05:55,170
It is nice.

1422
01:05:55,240 --> 01:05:56,410
Have you ever

1423
01:05:56,840 --> 01:05:59,410
- tried the snacks here?
- Yes, bread.

1424
01:05:59,480 --> 01:06:01,210
- Fish-shaped buns.
- And?

1425
01:06:01,280 --> 01:06:03,010
- Fish cakes.
- Fish cakes?

1426
01:06:03,080 --> 01:06:05,120
And I tried that thing.

1427
01:06:05,650 --> 01:06:06,720
That thing?

1428
01:06:06,780 --> 01:06:08,920
- "That thing" means...
- "That thing."

1429
01:06:08,990 --> 01:06:10,650
- What's "that thing"?
- A Jeolla Province thing.

1430
01:06:11,660 --> 01:06:13,190
- Oh, there are people inside.
- Goodness.

1431
01:06:13,260 --> 01:06:14,860
Oh, is this place a bit like...

1432
01:06:15,390 --> 01:06:17,330
- A reception room. Where are they?
- Hello.

1433
01:06:17,390 --> 01:06:19,130
No one seems to be here.

1434
01:06:19,200 --> 01:06:21,260
- Come sit over here.
- Sit over here.

1435
01:06:21,730 --> 01:06:23,200
- Come sit over here.
- Sit over here.

1436
01:06:23,270 --> 01:06:24,940
- What?
- He's a cute young man.

1437
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:27,040
- Yes, he is.
- He'll cook something nice.

1438
01:06:27,100 --> 01:06:29,140
- Yes. You and I both...
- Hang on.

1439
01:06:29,210 --> 01:06:31,110
Are you single or are you married?

1440
01:06:31,170 --> 01:06:32,480
He's awfully handsome.

1441
01:06:32,540 --> 01:06:34,380
Me? I'm not married yet.

1442
01:06:34,440 --> 01:06:36,750
Looks like it.
You look young like a child.

1443
01:06:36,810 --> 01:06:38,820
- I don't even have a girlfriend.
- No girlfriend either?

1444
01:06:38,880 --> 01:06:41,920
Find someone. Take your pick
out of the many out there.

1445
01:06:42,450 --> 01:06:45,290
PICK WHOM?

1446
01:06:46,190 --> 01:06:47,560
There are tons of funny people.

1447
01:06:47,860 --> 01:06:48,990
That was hilarious.

1448
01:06:49,060 --> 01:06:50,660
You remind me of my grandmother.

1449
01:06:50,730 --> 01:06:52,830
Oh, my. That would be a problem.

1450
01:06:53,430 --> 01:06:55,370
What do you think
I do for a living, ma'am?

1451
01:06:55,430 --> 01:06:56,970
- Could you be a chef?
- He's a chef.

1452
01:06:57,030 --> 01:07:00,740
- I can tell. You can cook.
- You're plump and cute.

1453
01:07:02,540 --> 01:07:04,670
- I'm not a chef, ma'am.
- You are.

1454
01:07:04,740 --> 01:07:05,880
- You are...
- No.

1455
01:07:05,940 --> 01:07:08,210
My third son's son looks like this.

1456
01:07:08,280 --> 01:07:10,410
He makes great vegetable pancakes.

1457
01:07:10,780 --> 01:07:12,220
Yes. You're adorable.

1458
01:07:12,280 --> 01:07:15,350
- I didn't eat any.
- You look like my grandson.

1459
01:07:15,420 --> 01:07:17,250
- You're sweet.
- You know

1460
01:07:17,320 --> 01:07:18,920
I'm not popular with young people.

1461
01:07:19,290 --> 01:07:21,320
- Why not?
- I'm popular with the elderly.

1462
01:07:22,360 --> 01:07:24,260
- We like cute folks.
- Because I look like a plump pig.

1463
01:07:24,330 --> 01:07:27,000
- You don't look like a pig.
- There are so many piggy people now.

1464
01:07:28,100 --> 01:07:29,530
- Because they eat well.
- I'll get an apron.

1465
01:07:29,600 --> 01:07:31,200
My oldest grandson is a pig, too.

1466
01:07:31,940 --> 01:07:35,540
You know which one. He's fat
and is working out to lose weight.

1467
01:07:35,940 --> 01:07:38,210
- He lost a bit.
- My tummy's getting fatter.

1468
01:07:38,940 --> 01:07:41,080
Yours isn't that fat at all.

1469
01:07:41,140 --> 01:07:43,110
Plump people are cute.

1470
01:07:43,180 --> 01:07:44,850
- Plump people are cute?
- Yes.

1471
01:07:44,920 --> 01:07:46,550
If you have a plump body

1472
01:07:46,620 --> 01:07:48,450
you have plump hands and fingers.

1473
01:07:48,520 --> 01:07:51,020
Anything made with such hands

1474
01:07:51,090 --> 01:07:52,390
- would be delicious.
- You're right.

1475
01:07:52,460 --> 01:07:55,130
Are your plump hands
the reason your food is good?

1476
01:07:55,190 --> 01:07:57,190
My food is disgustingly good.

1477
01:07:57,260 --> 01:07:58,760
- That's why.
- Yes.

1478
01:07:58,830 --> 01:08:02,370
I had so much fun meeting you.

1479
01:08:02,430 --> 01:08:03,970
- It's good to have fun.
- Yes.

1480
01:08:04,030 --> 01:08:05,540
I'll cook you something tasty.

1481
01:08:06,170 --> 01:08:09,870
I'm excited that someone
like my grandson will cook for us.

1482
01:08:10,610 --> 01:08:13,040
FROM GUMDONGYI'S FAIRY GODMOTHER

1483
01:08:13,480 --> 01:08:15,780
TO A FAIRY GODMOTHER FOR THE LOCALS

1484
01:08:16,680 --> 01:08:18,980
HE BROUGHT AN INDUSTRIAL RICE COOKER

1485
01:08:19,820 --> 01:08:20,850
WHAT WILL HE BE COOKING?

1486
01:08:20,920 --> 01:08:22,450
Where's the cutting board?

1487
01:08:23,590 --> 01:08:25,890
SOMEONE APPEARS BEFORE HE EVEN STARTS

1488
01:08:26,860 --> 01:08:28,220
Hello, ma'am.

1489
01:08:28,830 --> 01:08:30,360
- Come over here.
- Hello.

1490
01:08:30,430 --> 01:08:33,360
I'm a visiting chef from Seoul
who came by to cook.

1491
01:08:33,760 --> 01:08:35,370
I see. Thank you.

1492
01:08:35,430 --> 01:08:36,770
Sit here and wait.

1493
01:08:37,500 --> 01:08:40,570
STARTING BY PREPPING
A HUGE SLAB OF MEAT

1494
01:08:40,970 --> 01:08:44,240
COOKING IN EARNEST

1495
01:08:44,710 --> 01:08:45,940
Welcome.

1496
01:08:46,010 --> 01:08:47,580
YET ANOTHER LADY COMES IN

1497
01:08:48,280 --> 01:08:49,980
You got a pretty new vest.

1498
01:08:50,780 --> 01:08:52,780
- My daughter took me shopping.
- Hello.

1499
01:08:52,850 --> 01:08:54,220
- Hello.
- You haven't eaten, have you?

1500
01:08:56,250 --> 01:08:58,790
Hang on. Where are the handsome...

1501
01:08:58,860 --> 01:09:00,560
WHERE ARE THE HANDSOME YOUNG MEN?

1502
01:09:00,620 --> 01:09:03,460
There used to be three handsome guys.

1503
01:09:03,530 --> 01:09:05,260
- Yes. They're...
- I'm the kitchen help.

1504
01:09:05,330 --> 01:09:06,930
I see they aren't here.

1505
01:09:09,930 --> 01:09:12,640
I think this chef
is the most handsome.

1506
01:09:13,640 --> 01:09:14,640
Since you're here...

1507
01:09:15,010 --> 01:09:17,840
Since you're here,
shall I make you <i>gukbap?</i>

1508
01:09:17,910 --> 01:09:20,010
I'd appreciate it
if you'd serve me some.

1509
01:09:20,810 --> 01:09:23,350
You look like
you'd be good at cooking.

1510
01:09:23,710 --> 01:09:25,680
My stomach isn't just any stomach.

1511
01:09:25,750 --> 01:09:26,880
It's a foodie bag.

1512
01:09:26,950 --> 01:09:29,350
- Oh, is it?
- It cost a fortune to build up.

1513
01:09:30,090 --> 01:09:31,920
HE'S RIGHT

1514
01:09:31,990 --> 01:09:33,260
Your teeth aren't well, are they?

1515
01:09:33,320 --> 01:09:36,290
- Do you have trouble chewing?
- It's fine.

1516
01:09:36,360 --> 01:09:38,530
- I'll make the meat tender.
- These are my real teeth.

1517
01:09:38,600 --> 01:09:39,760
The meat should be tender.

1518
01:09:39,830 --> 01:09:41,130
- Make it tender.
- Yes, tender.

1519
01:09:41,830 --> 01:09:42,830
Thank you.

1520
01:09:42,900 --> 01:09:46,070
- Mr. Cook will know what to do.
- "Mr. Cook."

1521
01:09:46,370 --> 01:09:47,970
He's a cook,
so I called him Mr. Cook.

1522
01:09:48,270 --> 01:09:50,370
- Call him a chef.
- A shelf?

1523
01:09:51,010 --> 01:09:54,110
A GENEROUS SERVING
OF PORK NECK AND SHOULDER

1524
01:09:54,180 --> 01:09:55,310
Is this too much?

1525
01:09:57,680 --> 01:10:02,420
COOKING EXTRA
FOR THE UNEXPECTED GUESTS

1526
01:10:03,350 --> 01:10:05,990
ALMOST TOO HEAVY TO LIFT

1527
01:10:07,460 --> 01:10:09,390
DRIED KELP TO ADD FLAVOR

1528
01:10:09,460 --> 01:10:10,890
I want some country food.

1529
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:18,230
WE DON'T SCRIMP ON GARLIC,
RADISH, AND WHOLE PEPPERS

1530
01:10:18,740 --> 01:10:20,370
CHEF NAM-NO'S
EASY-TO-MAKE SUYUK GUKBAP

1531
01:10:21,770 --> 01:10:25,280
COOKED FOR 2 HOURS
SO IT'S EXTRA TENDER FOR THE ELDERLY!

1532
01:10:26,280 --> 01:10:30,410
IN CASE IT'S NOT ENOUGH
FOR THE HUNGRY TRIO

1533
01:10:31,820 --> 01:10:37,190
HE QUICKLY PREPARES A CHICKEN DISH

1534
01:10:37,690 --> 01:10:42,490
We'll sell it, and my son-in-law
will build his house there.

1535
01:10:42,560 --> 01:10:44,430
He said something about vegetables.

1536
01:10:44,490 --> 01:10:45,860
It's hard doing this all on my own.

1537
01:10:47,030 --> 01:10:48,360
- Young man.
- Yes?

1538
01:10:48,430 --> 01:10:50,070
Can you make fish-shaped buns?

1539
01:10:50,970 --> 01:10:52,440
- Fish-shaped buns?
- Yes.

1540
01:10:53,170 --> 01:10:54,340
That's...

1541
01:10:55,070 --> 01:10:57,070
- I'd like two of each.
- Just a moment.

1542
01:10:57,140 --> 01:10:58,640
- I'll finish this first.
- Okay.

1543
01:10:59,880 --> 01:11:01,080
Fish-shaped buns?

1544
01:11:02,150 --> 01:11:03,410
I've never made them before.

1545
01:11:04,810 --> 01:11:07,480
HE GOES OUTSIDE TO CHECK THE BUN ZONE

1546
01:11:07,550 --> 01:11:09,050
How does this work?

1547
01:11:11,720 --> 01:11:15,960
AN OMINOUS GUST OF WIND

1548
01:11:16,030 --> 01:11:17,460
TARP FLAPPING

1549
01:11:17,890 --> 01:11:21,460
STARTLED

1550
01:11:23,570 --> 01:11:24,770
Do I make them out here?

1551
01:11:27,570 --> 01:11:29,370
What's up with the wind?

1552
01:11:30,110 --> 01:11:31,510
It's picking up.

1553
01:11:31,780 --> 01:11:32,980
It's too windy out there.

1554
01:11:33,480 --> 01:11:35,280
- There's a mold, so it's fine.
- I almost...

1555
01:11:35,580 --> 01:11:37,880
I almost got blown away.

1556
01:11:38,920 --> 01:11:40,450
You're too heavy to get blown away.

1557
01:11:41,180 --> 01:11:42,620
You're too heavy to get blown away.

1558
01:11:44,790 --> 01:11:46,090
You're too fat and heavy.

1559
01:11:46,160 --> 01:11:47,460
That's what I wanted to hear you say.

1560
01:11:47,520 --> 01:11:49,760
- Right?
- Lock that up.

1561
01:11:50,130 --> 01:11:51,330
Lock it up?

1562
01:11:52,730 --> 01:11:55,030
<i>The smell. It's making me hungry.</i>

1563
01:11:55,270 --> 01:11:58,770
<i>- This is our first time eating out.</i>
<i>- It is.</i>

1564
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:03,440
- You're working hard, Boss PARK.
- Thank you.

1565
01:12:03,510 --> 01:12:05,280
- Thank you, Chef Kwak.
- Gosh.

1566
01:12:05,940 --> 01:12:07,280
All of us.

1567
01:12:07,340 --> 01:12:08,910
- To your good health.
- Cheers.

1568
01:12:08,980 --> 01:12:10,510
Good job, everyone.

1569
01:12:10,580 --> 01:12:13,020
THEIR FIRST TEAM MEAL

1570
01:12:18,050 --> 01:12:20,990
STARTING OFF WITH SOME MAKGEOLLI

1571
01:12:21,060 --> 01:12:22,860
I can taste the strawberry.

1572
01:12:24,360 --> 01:12:29,130
THE EXHAUSTION OF THE HIKE
MELTED AWAY

1573
01:12:29,830 --> 01:12:32,300
SANG-YI DRINKS THE BROTH
INSTEAD OF THE ALCOHOL

1574
01:12:32,370 --> 01:12:34,000
Happy New Year, guys.

1575
01:12:35,070 --> 01:12:36,970
A BIG MOUTHFUL

1576
01:12:40,040 --> 01:12:42,980
STUFFING HIS MOUTH

1577
01:12:43,050 --> 01:12:44,580
IT'S TASTY

1578
01:12:45,920 --> 01:12:49,650
BOSS PARK USED TO EAT HURRIEDLY
IN CASE A CUSTOMER CAME BY

1579
01:12:50,150 --> 01:12:53,860
NOW HE CAN RELAX AND TAKE HIS TIME

1580
01:12:55,090 --> 01:12:58,600
A SATISFACTORY MEAL

1581
01:12:59,260 --> 01:13:00,500
It's so good.

1582
01:13:02,970 --> 01:13:07,840
CHEF KWAK WHO WAS ALWAYS
GETTING HIS HANDS WET IN THE KITCHEN

1583
01:13:07,900 --> 01:13:08,970
Isn't it incredible?

1584
01:13:09,040 --> 01:13:10,640
AND SANG-YI WHO WAS ALWAYS
RUNNING AFTER CUSTOMERS

1585
01:13:11,210 --> 01:13:14,380
FOR ONCE,
THEY CAN FOCUS ON THEIR FOOD!

1586
01:13:15,010 --> 01:13:16,450
Good job so far.

1587
01:13:16,510 --> 01:13:17,580
IT'S A SPECIAL DAY

1588
01:13:19,650 --> 01:13:24,720
A BUSINESS OWNER'S DAY OFF
IS A PRECIOUS LUXURY

1589
01:13:24,790 --> 01:13:27,220
Are you licensed
to drive large vehicles?

1590
01:13:28,160 --> 01:13:30,530
Large vehicles? No.
Should I get the license?

1591
01:13:31,430 --> 01:13:33,330
If there is such an opportunity

1592
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:36,130
and one of us
were to get that license

1593
01:13:37,170 --> 01:13:38,270
we could travel nationwide.

1594
01:13:38,330 --> 01:13:39,970
- That would be fun.
- Yes.

1595
01:13:40,500 --> 01:13:44,710
Let's go around and do magic.

1596
01:13:45,210 --> 01:13:46,410
That would be crazy.

1597
01:13:46,480 --> 01:13:48,610
We just have to change one word
in our barbershop's name.

1598
01:13:48,680 --> 01:13:50,550
To The Village Car.

1599
01:13:51,210 --> 01:13:53,220
- I like that. The Village Car.
- Right?

1600
01:13:54,150 --> 01:13:55,720
MAKING PLANS TO EXPAND OVER LUNCH

1601
01:13:55,790 --> 01:13:57,890
I'm pretty sure I can
get the license to drive a bus.

1602
01:13:57,950 --> 01:13:59,190
If someone is able to...

1603
01:13:59,820 --> 01:14:01,890
- That license...
- We need a makeup artist license.

1604
01:14:02,330 --> 01:14:04,430
Later on, we could do bridal makeup.

1605
01:14:04,490 --> 01:14:05,900
We can do everything.

1606
01:14:05,960 --> 01:14:08,330
We could go to a wedding and...

1607
01:14:08,400 --> 01:14:10,300
- Do their hair up.
- And make bouquets.

1608
01:14:10,370 --> 01:14:13,940
I'm actually pretty interested
in landscaping and stuff.

1609
01:14:14,670 --> 01:14:16,870
We're here to eat,
yet we're brainstorming for ideas.

1610
01:14:16,940 --> 01:14:18,240
Let's get the drone license, too.

1611
01:14:18,810 --> 01:14:20,810
- I was looking into that.
- Were you really?

1612
01:14:21,280 --> 01:14:23,050
We can go to island villages.

1613
01:14:23,110 --> 01:14:25,080
I'm licensed to steer small boats.

1614
01:14:25,780 --> 01:14:28,350
- That's right.
- I can drive boats.

1615
01:14:28,420 --> 01:14:29,690
Let's go around on that.

1616
01:14:30,150 --> 01:14:32,120
I must get
the hairdresser license first.

1617
01:14:33,120 --> 01:14:34,860
We work as a perfect team now.

1618
01:14:34,920 --> 01:14:36,630
We have perfect timing and teamwork.

1619
01:14:37,330 --> 01:14:39,830
Let's go to Fukuoka from Busan.

1620
01:14:39,900 --> 01:14:41,700
<i>- Irasshaimase.</i>
<i>- Irasshaimase.</i>

1621
01:14:41,760 --> 01:14:43,270
You speak Japanese.

1622
01:14:43,900 --> 01:14:45,270
We're talking all sorts of nonsense.

1623
01:14:46,140 --> 01:14:48,000
It's because you two drank alcohol.

1624
01:14:49,240 --> 01:14:50,740
- We lost control.
- It's strawberry-flavored.

1625
01:14:50,810 --> 01:14:52,210
- Let's drink.
- Let's drink.

1626
01:14:52,280 --> 01:14:55,580
- You two drank alcohol.
- Let's go, village barbers!

1627
01:14:55,650 --> 01:14:56,850
DAYDREAMING FOR A WHILE

1628
01:14:57,280 --> 01:15:01,420
WE'LL GO BACK
TO WORKING HARD TOMORROW

1629
01:15:01,850 --> 01:15:03,950
Do you think anyone
came by the barbershop?

1630
01:15:04,020 --> 01:15:05,120
I wonder.

1631
01:15:06,520 --> 01:15:08,590
- I smell something tasty.
- Do you?

1632
01:15:08,660 --> 01:15:10,330
What tasty food are you making?

1633
01:15:13,930 --> 01:15:19,300
THE PORK IS NICELY BOILED

1634
01:15:21,140 --> 01:15:26,740
THE ELDERLY WILL ENJOY
THE TENDER PORK NECK

1635
01:15:27,340 --> 01:15:29,950
NAM-NO TRIES THE FOOD

1636
01:15:31,110 --> 01:15:35,950
IT'S PERFECT

1637
01:15:37,120 --> 01:15:39,020
It can't be too big for them.

1638
01:15:39,090 --> 01:15:40,720
BITE-SIZED RADISH PIECES

1639
01:15:42,090 --> 01:15:44,330
- Do you want lots of green onions?
- Yes.

1640
01:15:44,390 --> 01:15:45,600
Lots of green onions.

1641
01:15:45,660 --> 01:15:46,930
The more the better.

1642
01:15:50,030 --> 01:15:55,610
HE WANTS TO SERVE THEM ON TIME

1643
01:15:56,740 --> 01:16:00,580
RUSHING ABOUT TO SET THE TABLE

1644
01:16:00,640 --> 01:16:01,940
I haven't worked this hard
in a while.

1645
01:16:02,410 --> 01:16:04,550
HE CAME ON THEIR DAY OFF
AND WORKED BUSILY

1646
01:16:04,610 --> 01:16:06,250
You might lose all the weight

1647
01:16:07,350 --> 01:16:08,350
and become good-looking.

1648
01:16:09,750 --> 01:16:11,550
- It smells nice.
- It took some work.

1649
01:16:12,520 --> 01:16:15,490
Let's hike the step and get in.

1650
01:16:16,690 --> 01:16:18,230
- Thank you.
- Sure.

1651
01:16:18,290 --> 01:16:20,000
Thank you for cooking for us.

1652
01:16:20,060 --> 01:16:21,800
- Who's the second eldest?
- Isn't this your kimchi?

1653
01:16:21,860 --> 01:16:23,170
- The second eldest.
- It is, isn't it?

1654
01:16:23,230 --> 01:16:24,500
- The second eldest.
- It's mine.

1655
01:16:24,570 --> 01:16:26,040
- You're the youngest?
- We're the same age.

1656
01:16:26,100 --> 01:16:27,400
Are you? I see.

1657
01:16:30,440 --> 01:16:33,210
She looks younger,
and I look older, right?

1658
01:16:33,280 --> 01:16:34,740
- Not at all.
- Right?

1659
01:16:34,810 --> 01:16:36,250
It's not nice to be older.

1660
01:16:36,310 --> 01:16:38,750
- It's nice to be older.
- It's not.

1661
01:16:38,820 --> 01:16:40,950
YOU SHOULD WATCH WHAT YOU SAY

1662
01:16:41,380 --> 01:16:43,290
Thank you for the food.

1663
01:16:43,350 --> 01:16:45,860
HOW DOES THE CHEF'S FOOD TASTE?

1664
01:16:45,920 --> 01:16:48,590
- It's good.
- It's good, Chef.

1665
01:16:48,660 --> 01:16:51,760
- Is it good?
- Have a bite. You did the cooking.

1666
01:16:51,830 --> 01:16:53,930
- It's really good.
- Hang on.

1667
01:16:54,000 --> 01:16:55,360
- It's good.
- See?

1668
01:16:55,430 --> 01:16:57,130
- It's good.
- Who made it?

1669
01:16:58,370 --> 01:17:01,440
OUR CUTE CHEF MADE IT

1670
01:17:01,500 --> 01:17:02,770
It's tasty.

1671
01:17:02,840 --> 01:17:03,970
It's nice.

1672
01:17:05,610 --> 01:17:08,410
- It's nice to see you enjoy it.
- I can't seem to find it.

1673
01:17:10,510 --> 01:17:12,220
My grandma...

1674
01:17:13,880 --> 01:17:16,120
I never got to cook for her
when she was alive.

1675
01:17:16,390 --> 01:17:18,020
- Not even once.
- We're eating it instead.

1676
01:17:18,090 --> 01:17:20,020
She knew I was into cooking.

1677
01:17:20,760 --> 01:17:24,660
- But I never cooked for her.
- I see, and that bothers you.

1678
01:17:25,700 --> 01:17:28,230
- So...
- You must be thinking of her.

1679
01:17:29,230 --> 01:17:31,930
- Will you be my grandma?
- Of course, I will.

1680
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:34,300
- Will you give me money if I visit?
- You bet.

1681
01:17:34,670 --> 01:17:36,310
Offering food just once isn't enough.

1682
01:17:36,370 --> 01:17:37,970
We should show our appreciation.
Have another.

1683
01:17:38,040 --> 01:17:39,310
Thank you.

1684
01:17:39,910 --> 01:17:41,580
Oh, it's so tasty.

1685
01:17:41,640 --> 01:17:42,810
It tastes good.

1686
01:17:42,880 --> 01:17:44,050
HE BECAME MUJU'S NEW GRANDSON

1687
01:17:44,110 --> 01:17:45,310
It's nicely cooked.

1688
01:17:45,380 --> 01:17:47,050
- It's nicely cooked.
- It's lovely.

1689
01:17:49,250 --> 01:17:50,590
Gosh, it's cold.

1690
01:17:50,950 --> 01:17:54,190
What's that noise? What's going on?

1691
01:17:56,390 --> 01:17:58,490
It wasn't the sound of a passing car.

1692
01:17:59,760 --> 01:18:02,270
FISH-SHAPED BUNS

1693
01:18:02,330 --> 01:18:05,000
HOW ARE THEY MADE?

1694
01:18:05,070 --> 01:18:08,200
From what I've noticed,
they put in the batter first.

1695
01:18:08,270 --> 01:18:09,440
- Batter first.
- Yes.

1696
01:18:09,510 --> 01:18:11,970
Then the red bean goes in the middle.

1697
01:18:12,740 --> 01:18:17,410
HE STARTS OFF BY DOING WHAT SHE SAID

1698
01:18:18,950 --> 01:18:23,690
IT LOOKS PRETTY GOOD
CONSIDERING IT'S HIS FIRST TRY

1699
01:18:23,750 --> 01:18:24,820
MELODY RINGS OUT

1700
01:18:24,890 --> 01:18:26,160
Why? What's wrong?

1701
01:18:28,360 --> 01:18:30,530
What? What the heck do you want?

1702
01:18:30,590 --> 01:18:32,230
WHAT'S WRONG WITH THIS?

1703
01:18:34,730 --> 01:18:36,370
It's leaking out the side.

1704
01:18:38,470 --> 01:18:39,840
THE TIMER CAUSED SOME CHAOS

1705
01:18:39,900 --> 01:18:41,170
Do I flip it?

1706
01:18:41,240 --> 01:18:42,570
Does this go this way?

1707
01:18:42,640 --> 01:18:43,840
How does this work?

1708
01:18:43,910 --> 01:18:45,370
CONFUSED

1709
01:18:46,780 --> 01:18:48,340
- You need to wait.
- We must wait?

1710
01:18:50,150 --> 01:18:52,880
Young people can get it in one try.

1711
01:18:52,950 --> 01:18:55,080
You've made a lot already.

1712
01:18:55,150 --> 01:18:57,450
- It's not hard.
- We just need two rounds.

1713
01:18:57,520 --> 01:19:01,060
- But it's cold out here.
- I bet, since you're wearing that.

1714
01:19:01,520 --> 01:19:04,030
- Oh, hot.
- Use a spoon.

1715
01:19:04,090 --> 01:19:05,330
Poke them with this.

1716
01:19:05,730 --> 01:19:07,700
- There must be tongs.
- It's over there.

1717
01:19:07,760 --> 01:19:08,970
There must be tongs.

1718
01:19:09,030 --> 01:19:11,430
To pick them up. That's it.

1719
01:19:11,500 --> 01:19:13,270
It's your first time,
so you don't know how to do it.

1720
01:19:14,200 --> 01:19:17,110
Put that in there. Yes. And another.

1721
01:19:17,170 --> 01:19:18,440
I can do better after a few tries.

1722
01:19:18,510 --> 01:19:19,740
- Yes.
- You would.

1723
01:19:19,810 --> 01:19:22,610
- Since you know how to cook.
- Oh, thank you.

1724
01:19:22,680 --> 01:19:23,680
MAKING BUNS UNDER THEIR ENCOURAGEMENT

1725
01:19:23,910 --> 01:19:25,210
- Let's go now.
- Yes.

1726
01:19:25,280 --> 01:19:27,080
Let's get going.

1727
01:19:27,150 --> 01:19:28,580
Thank you.

1728
01:19:28,650 --> 01:19:31,350
- Ma'am. I wish you good health.
- Bye.

1729
01:19:31,420 --> 01:19:32,620
Look after yourself.

1730
01:19:32,690 --> 01:19:34,260
Thanks for the food.

1731
01:19:34,320 --> 01:19:35,690
THE FAIRY GODMOTHER
WAITS FOR THE TRIO

1732
01:19:37,030 --> 01:19:39,930
THE TRIO HEAD HOME
WITH NO IDEA THAT NAM-NO'S HERE

1733
01:19:40,260 --> 01:19:43,700
<i>What kind of love this is</i>

1734
